<li><cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFWeyl1952"><a href="/wiki/Hermann_Weyl" title="Hermann Weyl">Weyl, Hermann</a> (1952). <i>Symmetry</i>. Princeton, NJ: Princeton University Press. <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0691023743" class="internal">ISBN 0-691-02374-3</a>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Symmetry&amp;rft.aulast=Weyl&amp;rft.aufirst=Hermann&amp;rft.au=Weyl%2C+Hermann&amp;rft.date=1952&amp;rft.place=Princeton%2C+NJ&amp;rft.pub=Princeton+University+Press&amp;rft.isbn=0-691-02374-3&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Platonic_solid"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li>"Strena seu de nive sexangula" (On the Six-Cornered Snowflake), 1611 paper by Kepler which discussed the reason for the six-angled shape of the snow crystals and the forms and symmetries in nature. Talks about platonic solids.</li>
</ul>
